# labwc autostart — runs once when the labwc session starts.
# Installs to ~/.config/labwc/autostart (user). labwc executes it with /bin/sh.
#
# Initial-cursor hide. With <touch mouseEmulation="no"/> (rc.xml) and no physical
# mouse, NO pointer-motion event ever fires, so the page never gets pointer focus
# and its CSS `cursor:none` never applies — labwc's default pointer just sits at
# screen center from boot until the first touch (after which it stays gone, since
# mouseEmulation="no" means touch can't re-summon it). This nudges the virtual
# pointer a few times so that, once the fullscreen Chromium surface has mapped, a
# motion event reaches it, Chromium applies `cursor:none`, and the cursor hides
# with no human touch required. Requires wlrctl (apt).
#
# Looped, not a single move: the Chromium kiosk is a SEPARATE user service, so its
# surface may not be mapped yet when this autostart runs. ~10s of 0.5s-spaced
# nudges rides out that startup gap; each move is 1px and the cursor is hidden
# anyway, so the drift is invisible. Backgrounded so it never blocks the session.
#
# NOTE: this only hides the cursor once Chromium is up; the brief default pointer
# during the pre-paint black gap is not addressed here (would need a transparent
# cursor theme) and is accepted as-is.
[ -x "$(command -v wlrctl)" ] && (
  for _ in $(seq 1 20); do
    wlrctl pointer move 1 1
    sleep 0.5
  done
) &
